// C3: Physical sensing components
instance MotorEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Motor encoder mounted directly on the permanent magnet synchronous motor, providing real-time position feedback via input current and output angle data."
    DTDFVocab:producedData MotorEncoderDataTransmitted
]

instance SecondaryEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Secondary encoder positioned behind the gearbox, providing redundant position feedback via input current and output angle data."
    DTDFVocab:producedData SecondaryEncoderDataTransmitted
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance MotorEncoderDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    base:desc "Real-time streaming of input current and output angle data from the motor encoder via MQTT protocol."
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MotorEncoder
]

instance SecondaryEncoderDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    base:desc "Real-time streaming of input current and output angle data from the secondary encoder via MQTT protocol."
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom SecondaryEncoder
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance FrictionDynamicsModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Executable simulation model of the robot's friction dynamics within the first axis, developed using MathWorks Simulink for motion control strategy refinement."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkEnabler
]

instance RobotArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Structural and behavioral model of the MABI MAX 100 robot's architecture using SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs) and state machines."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SysmlEnabler
]

instance SensorDataTraces : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Aggregated and contextualized time-series data traces from motor and secondary encoders (input current and output angle) for real-time monitoring."
    DTDFVocab:fromData MotorEncoderDataTransmitted, SecondaryEncoderDataTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo MqttEnabler
]

instance ControlStrategyData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed data from friction dynamics simulations used to validate and refine motion control strategies."
    DTDFVocab:fromData MotorEncoderDataTransmitted, SecondaryEncoderDataTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkEnabler
]

// C11: Enablers
instance SysmlEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "SysML-based modeling environment for structural and behavioral architecture definition using Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs) and state machines."
    DTDFVocab:enables RobotArchitectureService, MonitoringService
]

instance SimulinkEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks Simulink environment for executable friction dynamics modeling and control strategy validation."
    DTDFVocab:enables SimulationService, ControlStrategyService
]

instance MqttEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MQTT protocol implementation for low-latency, lightweight real-time streaming of sensor data traces from physical robot to digital shadow."
    DTDFVocab:enables MonitoringService, DataAggregationService
]

instance SinumerikControllerEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Siemens SINUMERIK controller interface executing motion commands and interfacing with sensor data streams."
    DTDFVocab:enables ControlStrategyService
]

// C6: Services
instance MonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Real-time dashboard-based visualization of aggregated sensor data traces (motor torque, gearbox temperature, encoder feedback) for operational oversight."
    DTDFVocab:provides OperationalMonitoringInsight
]

instance SimulationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Integration with MathWorks Simulink for behavioral modeling and validation of the robot's functional and logical architecture."
    DTDFVocab:provides FrictionAnalysisInsight, FailureScenarioInsight
]

instance DataAggregationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Collection and processing of contextual data traces (sensor readings, actuator commands) into structured digital representations."
    DTDFVocab:provides DataContextualizationInsight
]

instance ControlStrategyService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Offline testing and refinement of motion control strategies based on friction dynamics simulation results."
    DTDFVocab:provides MotionOptimizationInsight
]

instance RobotArchitectureService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Structural and behavioral architecture definition using SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs) and state machines."
    DTDFVocab:provides SystemArchitectureInsight
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance OperationalMonitoringInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Real-time operational status visualization for manufacturing engineers and maintenance technicians."
]

instance FrictionAnalysisInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Detailed analysis of friction dynamics within the first robot axis to identify performance bottlenecks."
]

instance FailureScenarioInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Validation of control strategies against simulated failure scenarios for predictive maintenance."
]

instance DataContextualizationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Structured representation of sensor data traces with contextual metadata for analysis."
]

instance MotionOptimizationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Optimized motion profiles based on friction dynamics simulation results."
]

instance SystemArchitectureInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Comprehensive structural and behavioral representation of the MABI MAX 100 robot architecture."
]

// C1: Physical Twin Components
instance PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "High-precision motor providing torque and position control for the first robot axis."
]

instance Gearbox : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Mechanical transmission system reducing motor speed while increasing torque for the robot axis."
]

instance SINUMERIKController : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Primary control interface executing motion commands and interfacing with sensor data streams."
]

// C2: Acting Components
instance MotionControlActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Actuator executing refined motion control strategies based on friction dynamics analysis."
]

// C17: Environment
instance RobotAxisEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:desc "Physical environment containing the first vertical axis of the MABI MAX 100 serial robot."
    base:contains PermanentMagnetSynchronousMotor, Gearbox, MotorEncoder, SecondaryEncoder, SINUMERIKController
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system for the serial robot MABI MAX 100 is modeled using **SysML** for structural and behavioral descriptions, including **internal block diagrams (IBDs)** for component-connector architectures and **state machines** (SysML v1.7) for behavioral modeling. The system integrates with **executable simulation models** (e.g., MathWorks MATLAB Simulink) for dynamic behavior representation. No explicit orchestration patterns (e.g., microservices, event-driven architectures) or resource management mechanisms are detailed, but the system relies on **heterogeneous tool integration** (SysML + Simulink) to unify modeling and simulation. The document does not mention architecture patterns like ACME, AADL, or MontiArc for this specific use case."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system employs **MathWorks Simulink** for modeling **friction within the first axis** and **rigidity in robot joints**, using executable simulation models to replicate physical behavior. **Validation** is performed by comparing **simulated data against measured data** to quantify deviations and ensure model accuracy. No explicit mention of uncertainty quantification, error detection mechanisms (e.g., threshold-based anomaly detection), or quality assurance processes is provided in the document."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system for the serial robot MABI MAX 100 integrates with external systems via **MQTT** for streaming time-series data from the physical robot axis to the digital shadow. The system leverages **Asset Administration Shells (AAS)** as a standardized interface for data exchange, enabling interoperability with enterprise systems or other Digital Twins. No explicit dependencies on protocols like OPC UA or REST are mentioned, but the use of MQTT and AAS implies adherence to **Industry 4.0 interoperability standards**. The document does not specify integration patterns (e.g., publish-subscribe, API gateways) beyond the MQTT-AAS pipeline."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system adheres to **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** standards, including **SysML (Systems Modeling Language)** for system architecture and behavior modeling. For **architecture description**, it leverages **ADLs (Architecture Description Languages)** such as **ACME**, **AADL**, and **MontiArc**, which are standardized for component-based system design. **SysML v1.7** supports state machines for behavioral modeling, aligning with **OMG (Object Management Group) standards**. Interoperability is facilitated through integration with **MathWorks Simulink** and other simulation tools, though no specific interoperability standards (e.g., OPC UA, FIWARE) are mentioned. The **Digital Shadow Reference Model** (Fig. 1) implies compliance with **manufacturing-specific data aggregation standards**, but no explicit certification or compliance frameworks (e.g., ISO 23247, IEC 62443) are referenced. The document does not specify **industry standards** (e.g., NIST, IEEE) or **compliance requirements** beyond MBSE and ADL methodologies."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system incorporates **safety-critical mechanisms** such as the **safety cell** (as referenced in the MABI robotic arm documentation [44]), which restricts the working range of the robotic system to prevent collisions and ensure operator safety. The **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** framework ([46], [47], [50]) provides a standardized structure for integrating safety-related metadata, operational constraints, and compliance requirements for industrial assets. Additionally, **data streaming protocols** like **MQTT** ([52]) are employed for real-time communication, though explicit cybersecurity measures (e.g., encryption, authentication protocols) are not detailed in the provided documents. The **RAMI4.0 reference architecture** ([48], [49]) aligns with Industry 4.0 safety standards but does not specify granular security controls. **Fail-safe mechanisms** are implied through the use of structured simulation models (e.g., MathWorks MATLAB Simulink for executable models [43]) to validate safety-critical behaviors, but no explicit threat mitigation strategies or risk assessment methodologies are documented."
]